  "texts": [
    "Related worksThe remote sensing image scene classification strategies can be divided into three groups based on the extracted features' semantic levels: high-levelfeatures, mid-level features, and low-level features.",
    "The low-level feature methods aim to represent an image by extracting its fundamental properties before identifying the scene.",
    "So, feature vectors generated from lowlevel visual qualities are commonly used to describe remote sensing image scenes, divided into global and local feature vectors.",
    "Local feature descriptors, such as the histogram of oriented gradients (HOG) and the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT), are commonly employed to represent the local structures of remote sensing pictures for conveying complicated structural information.",
    "While global feature descriptors such as texture feature and colour histogram are commonly used to characterize the spatial arrangements of images."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}